public class MultipleRequester<Type>
extends EasyRequest

Currently the preferred way to make any application/x-www-form-urlencoded requests.

It allows the user to send multiple requests, each with it's own individual handler that is matched back to it when a response is returned.

The preferred way to use this is to subclass it for each type of request you would like to make. So one per address usually. In the new constructor you should pass in all the defaults the particular request will need. This allows you to use your subclass with a default constructor, avoiding errors.

There are a couple of methods you can override to affect behaviour:

  • received(Object, boolean, String)
  • getArgs()

And use go(uk.ac.imperial.vazels.reef.client.RequestHandler) to actually send a request.

Description copied from class: EasyRequest
Callback for any responses.

This will always receive a ticket identifying the originating request. If something goes wrong with sending or receiving the response, all other parameters will be null. Otherwise the parameters will be filled in where possible (depending on the returned code).

Specified by:
requested in class EasyRequest
Parameters:
ticket - Identifies the originating request.
code - The returned response code.
reason - The text following the response code.
content - A String containing the response data (without headers).

getArgs

protected EasyRequest.QueryArg[] getArgs()
Provides the query arguments for any request.

This is called for each request and should be overridden if the request is to provide any QueryArgs. In current implementations of this method, we subclass MultipleRequester as an inner class of the class using it. This means that we can rip query arguments straight from the class that contains the relevant data.

Returns:
A list of QueryArgs to provide with the request.

received

protected void received(Type reply,
                        boolean success,
                        java.lang.String message)
A callback that is run for every received response.

This has the same input as RequestHandler.handle(Object, boolean, String) and is called directly before the individual response handler.

You should only override this if you need to use it.

go

public void go(RequestHandler<Type> handler,
               java.lang.String addrExt)
Send a request to a modified address.

This works just as go(RequestHandler) but modifies the address that the request is sent to.

Parameters:
handler - The handler that is called on result of this request.
addrExt - A String tagged to the end of the request address. For instance a request constructed with the request address "/settings/" and with addrExt as "global" will send the request to "/settings/global".
